Method 1

Code rewrite

require(dplyr)
data <- data.frame(id = c(1,1,2), outcome = c(TRUE, TRUE, FALSE))
distinct(data, id, .keep_all = TRUE) %>%
    select(outcome)

Youâll need to edit your code when there are new breaking changes

Method 2

Install the old version

remotes::install_version("dplyr", "0.4.3")

(Non-)method 3

Using MRAN Posit Public Package Manager (P3M)

p3m <- "https://packagemanager.posit.co/cran/2016-01-10"
options(repos = c(REPO_NAME = p3m))
install.packages("dplyr") # install 0.4.3?

require(dplyr)
data <- data.frame(id = c(1,1,2), outcome = c(TRUE, TRUE, FALSE))
distinct(data, id) %>%
    select(outcome)

It wonât work because P3M can only go as far back as 2017 Oct 10. It installs the âtime-appropriateâ recursive dependencies. But it mixes old packages with your current system library. Of course, you can use install.packages(âdplyrâ, lib = âxyzâ)

(Non-)method 4

Using renv 1.0.0

require(renv)
renv::init() ## restart
install.packages("dplyr")
renv::checkout(date = "2016-01-10")
renv::snapshot()
require(dplyr)
data <- data.frame(id = c(1,1,2), outcome = c(TRUE, TRUE, FALSE))
distinct(data, id) %>%
    select(outcome)

It wonât work also because P3M can only go as far back as 2017 Oct 10.

Our solution: rang

  • Date-based pinning (like P3M, renv)
  • Create container images (like Rocker)
  • Support CRAN, Bioconductor, GitHub, & local packages
  • Resolve system dependencies, e.g.Â libxml2
  • Depend on r-hub, CRAN, Bioconductor, GitHub API; doesnât use P3M
  • Interoperability with renv (lockfile, project scanning)
  • Can go as far back as 2001-08-31 (or R 1.3.1)

We are talking about Tony Blair and Bush 43 (and thatâs two weeks before 911)

Usage: Resolve

Resolve the dependency graph

library(rang)
graph <- resolve(pkgs = c("dplyr"), snapshot_date = "2016-01-10")
graph
resolved: 1 package(s). Unresolved package(s): 0 
$`cran::dplyr`
The latest version of `dplyr` [cran] at 2016-01-10 was 0.4.3, which has 7 unique dependencies (7 with no dependencies.)

Usage: Dockerize

dockerize(rang = graph,
          output_dir = "~/dplyr_example",
          no_rocker = TRUE,  # recommended
          cache = TRUE) # recommended

Dockerfile

FROM scratch
ADD /cache/debian/rootfs.tar.xz /
ENV TZ UTC
RUN ln -snf /usr/share/zoneinfo/$TZ /etc/localtime \
    && echo $TZ > /etc/timezone \
    && apt-get update -qq \
    && apt-get install wget locales build-essential r-base-dev  -y
ENV RANG_PATH /rang.R
ENV COMPILE_PATH /compile_r.sh
ENV CACHE_PATH /cache
COPY rang.R /rang.R
COPY compile_r.sh /compile_r.sh
COPY cache/rpkgs /cache/rpkgs
COPY cache/rsrc /cache/rsrc
RUN apt-get update -qq \
    && apt-get install -y libpcre3-dev zlib1g-dev pkg-config libcurl4-openssl-dev
RUN bash $COMPILE_PATH 3.2.3
CMD ["R"]

Build and launch

cd ~/dplyr_example
docker build -t dplyr .
docker run --rm --name "dplyr" -ti dplyr
